Executive Summary

Designing a community-centric participation app requires clear orientation, low cognitive load, and respectful personalization. Key UX heuristics (Nielsen–Norman) mandate recognition over recall, clear visual hierarchy, and progressive disclosure. Home pages should greet users with a simple, high-level overview of how they might engage (e.g. “Continue →”, “Explore →”), not an overwhelming feed. Interactions and visuals must reveal complexity only as needed (progressive disclosure).

For map-based exploration and rhythm visualizations, different map modes serve different tasks. A “Live Map” shows concrete upcoming events (bounded “kernels”) and venue anchors; a “Rhythm Map” shows ambient community activity cycles (soft fields that morph over time); an “Adjacent Map” reveals connections between events/communities as traces; a “Familiar Map” highlights user’s existing interests. Graphics should use SVG overlays (for interactivity and accessibility) and base map via Leaflet. Visual design should employ Gestalt grouping (proximity, common regions) and color blending for overlapping communities (with CIE-LCh blending for intuitiveness).

Interactions must offer lightweight personalization without hardening identity. Allow users to choose a stance each session (e.g. Continue / Explore / Deepen / Create / Rest) so that the UI adjusts to their current intent, while still exposing adjacent possibilities. Ethical UX and privacy require transparency, user control, diversity, and inclusion; avoid over-filtering or dark patterns. Accessibility (WCAG/ARIA) demands keyboard navigation and alt-text for map layers, high contrast, color-blind–friendly palettes, and minimizing required personal data (data minimization per GDPR).

This report compiles actionable guidelines and patterns across 1) general UX/UI principles, 2) orientation/home design, 3) map and rhythm visualizations, 4) interaction flows and personalization, 5) ethics/privacy/accessibility, 6) visual/animation language, 7) prototyping/implementation notes, 8) tone/microcopy, and 9) research methods and metrics.
1. UX Principles and Heuristics

    Nielsen’s Usability Heuristics: Prioritize visibility of system status, user control, consistency, error prevention, and flexibility. In particular, “recognition rather than recall” means surface familiar cues (community names, icons, events) instead of forcing users to remember details. Provide immediate feedback for actions (saving an event, switching mode).
    Cognitive Load: Reduce unnecessary load. Only present information needed now; chunk related items together. Avoid overwhelming text. Use progressive disclosure: e.g. show 2–3 “preview” items per section with a “Show more” to reveal full lists.
    Gestalt Principles: Use proximity, common region, similarity, and continuity to group and distinguish UI elements. For example, related controls or event lists should have common containers. Use consistent spacing and boundaries to indicate grouping.
    Visual Hierarchy: Guide attention via size, contrast, and color. On the landing page, have one dominant “window” (e.g. Rhythm preview) and secondary panels, not six equal cards. Emphasize the primary action by scale and color, minimize secondary actions.
    Recognition over Recall: Present choices that are immediately recognizable (community names, logos, tags) rather than asking users to type or remember choices. For example, use known community logos or color-coded tags in suggestions.
    Jakob’s Law: Make the UI feel familiar. Use common patterns (top nav bar, hero section, cards, modals) so users leverage past experience. For instance, a map with a slider is a known convention for timeline filtering.
    Accessibility: Follow WCAG. Ensure keyboard operability for maps, provide alt-text or ARIA labels for every graphical element. Do not rely on color alone – use shapes, patterns, or labels for color-blind users. Provide high contrast for text and important shapes.
    Feedback & Affordances: Make interactive elements clearly clickable. Buttons (e.g. “Explore”) should look like buttons. Use micro-interactions (hover highlights) sparingly to indicate interactivity without distracting.
    Progress Indicators: For processes (e.g. event creation or a multi-step onboarding), show steps or progress bars so users know where they are.

2. Orientation-first Home & Navigation

    Orientation vs. Action: The home (“orientation page”) should ask how the user wants to engage, not impose a task. Present a short menu of stances, each illustrated. The user’s intent (mode) guides the next view.
    Hero Section: The top should have a concise greeting/prompt (e.g. “How would you like to be with the field today?”) with one primary action or highlighted mode. Use a hero that conveys the app’s purpose (e.g. a map or field image with a short tagline).
    Buttons vs Windows: Instead of dense text, use large “window” cards with minimal copy and vivid previews. Each window covers one mode (Continue, Explore, Rhythm, Deepen, Create, Rest). Only one or two windows should be prominent at a time; others can be shown on demand or as smaller links (progressive disclosure).
    Recognition of Context: Show “your world” at a glance. For example:
        Continue / Familiar: display followed community logos, next saved events, or a familiar spot on a tiny map snippet.
        Explore / Adjacent: show a preview like “CI Aarhus → Ecstatic Dance” to illustrate adjacency.
        Rhythm: show a small weekly wheel or heatmap snippet with days/venues highlighted.
        Deepen: list one or two ongoing labs or volunteer options in a followed community.
        Create: show a “+ Create event” card or a draft event card.
        Rest: show upcoming commitments summary, or “Nothing urgent today” message.
    Hierarchy and Scanning: Use headlines plus 2–3 bullet lines per window (no paragraphs). Emphasize keywords (community names, times) in bold. Use whitespace to separate the sections distinctly.
    Navigation Controls: A clear nav bar for global navigation (Map, Communities, Events, Profile) should persist. However, the home itself should primarily push people into one of the stance modes.
    CTA Labels: Use action-focused verbs (“Explore”, “Continue”, “Deepen”, etc.) as buttons. Do not use generic labels like “Submit”.

3. Map and Rhythm Visualizations
Map Modes

Implement at least four map modes, each with its own visual grammar:

    Live Map (Explore/Map View) – Question: “What is happening here soon?”
    Elements:
        Event kernels: Bounded blobs or icons at event locations (circle, rectangle). Encoded with: size ~ attendance, color ~ primary community. They have solid or dashed outlines to indicate access (public vs member-only).
        Venues: Minor anchor markers (diamond or dot). Highlight only when active or hovered.
        Community fields: Very light, translucent glow around areas to hint where that community is active now. (Optional background tone.)
        Time slider: A horizontal time scrubber (day/week).
        Interaction: Click an event to see details. Zoom/pan with Leaflet; clusters merge at small zoom.
        Design: Crisp shapes, minimal animation (maybe pulse on upcoming event).

    Rhythm Map – Question: “How does the field move through time?”
    Elements:
        Ambient fields: Organic blobs (SVG paths) around venues or clusters, colored by community. They morph subtly as time changes. Use smooth edges, low opacity.
        Animation: As the timeline (morning→night or Mon→Sun) plays, blob size and color blend shifts. For example, venue gets a CI-blue blob Tuesday AM, Circling-magenta blob Thursday PM, etc. Overlapping events form blended colors (mixed in CIE-LCh for better recognition).
        Regularity encoding: Steady rhythms have opaque, continuous blobs; sporadic ones are fainter, flickering.
        Selector: A circular “week dial” or timeline. User scrubs through week.
        Interaction: Clicking a blob opens a panel: “Pattern (usual activity) + Doors (next events/ways to participate)”.
        Design: Soothing, soft motion, not frantic. The map itself can auto-play or user-stepped.

    Familiar Territory Map – Question: “Where are the parts of the field I already know?”
    Elements:
        Highlight only the communities and venues the user follows or attends. E.g. color-fade others gray.
        Show saved/attending events prominently.
        Possibly dim out unrelated communities.
        Design: Clear, stable, no surprises – solid shapes, no animation. The idea is reassurance.

    Adjacent Worlds Map – Question: “What is connected to my interests?”
    Elements:
        Source: User selects a known event/community as start.
        Traces: Animated or static paths leading from the source to related nodes (future events, other communities). For example, a curved arrow or dotted line from a Wednesday CI event to a Thursday Circling event.
        Nodes: Could light up other events/venues.
        Interaction: Click “More like this” on an event card to trigger an animation of particles following those lines.
        Design: Trajectories or pulses in the same color family, showing flow. Keep on only while exploring to avoid clutter.

    Wider Field Map – Question: “What is happening in nearby cities/regions?”
    Elements:
        Geographical clusters (cities as points).
        Thick directional lines between cities for strong exchange (e.g. Aarhus–Copenhagen).
        Node color blends showing dominant practices.
        Possibly a simplified non-geo “community graph” (separate view or toggled).
        Design: Abstract, low detail, focus on hubs and flows.

Visual Encoding and Interactions

    Color Blending: When multiple communities overlap (in one area or event), blend their colors. Use light desaturated tints for fields, richer tints for event blobs. CIE-LCh blending is recommended (more perceptually uniform). Avoid more than ~5–7 key colors for easy identification. Always include a legend or interaction to reveal meaning of a blend.
    Shapes: Use distinct shapes or icons for venues (e.g. square/diamond) vs events (circles, blobs). This aids those with color vision deficiencies. Provide patterns or outlines if needed.
    Animation: Use subtle motion only when it clarifies relationships (e.g. map transitions, time scrubbing, trace drawing). Avoid continuous animations that distract. Provide user control to play/pause rhythms.
    Performance: Prefer SVG overlays for interactive elements (they integrate into the DOM and support ARIA). Use Canvas only if we must render thousands of nodes (unlikely at community scale). For performance, cluster overlapping events or switch to heatmap at high zoom levels.
    Pan/Zoom: Use Leaflet for base map. Ensure layers reproject on zoom. For dense areas (Godsbanen), consider compound markers or area fields rather than dozens of points.
    Responsive: On mobile, collapse to a simpler map view or adapt filters. Make sure legends and controls are tappable.

