4. Interaction Patterns

    Onboarding: For new users, a brief guided tour can highlight the main modes (Continue/Explore/etc). Use tooltips pointing at “Explore” and a preview. But avoid forcing an account immediately; allow some browsing anonymously.
    Stance Selection: Each session or on landing, allow the user to pick a stance (e.g. via a segmented control or tabbed interface). Save preference between sessions but never assume it’s fixed (“choose again” easily).
    Light Preference Capture: Instead of deep profiles, use checkboxes or tags for interests (e.g. “Contact Improvisation, Ecstatic Dance, Meditation”) on signup. But also learn passively: e.g. remember communities they follow and what events they bookmark. Allow easy editing.
    Progressive Personalization: Start with minimal assumptions. Show broad, diverse options by default; gradually bias suggestions if user explicitly “follows” communities or attends events. Always allow users to override (“I’m actually more into Circling now”).
    Feedback Loop: When user acts (saves event, suggests to community), reflect it in the interface promptly (increment counters, show them in “Your Activity”).
    Moding as Consent: The stance modes are a form of explicit UX tuning. For example, if user chooses “Deepen”, bias event lists towards ongoing series or labs in their communities. If “Explore”, show new community stuff. This respects user agency.
    Onboarding Community Creation: Stewards should have an easy “pulse dashboard” and “create event” prompts. For facilitators, emphasize how to “connect to communities” (via tagging events).
    Error Handling: Use inline validation on forms (e.g. event creation). Show clear error messages (“Time cannot be in the past”).

5. Ethics, Privacy, Accessibility

    Privacy-by-Design: Collect only necessary data. E.g., use optional name (social login okay), optional profile info. Do not track users across sites. Comply with GDPR:
        Consent: ask before sending notifications or newsletters.
        Data Minimization: Only keep personal info needed to display their profile, RSVP to events, etc.
        Right to Erasure: Allow users to delete account and data.
    No Dark Patterns: Don’t “nudge” users into more participation or paid membership. Avoid social feedback loops like “Only 1 spot left!” which may manipulate choice.
    Ethical Personalization: Follow guidelines: transparency (“Why am I seeing this event?”), opt-out (“Reset suggestions”), introducing diverse content. Prioritize well-being (e.g. content warnings for sensitive events). Ensure underrepresented communities have visibility.
    Inclusive Design: Interface should work with screen readers (ARIA labels on map overlays). Ensure contrast meets WCAG2.1 (AA minimum). Keyboard navigation must be fully supported (e.g. moving through events in the map). Provide text alternatives for any important imagery.
    Data Security: Use HTTPS, secure user data properly. If storing location data (user’s city, etc.), be explicit about usage. Possibly allow an “incognito” mode for browsing without login.

6. Visual & Motion Guidelines

    Color Palette: Choose a limited palette of 5–7 vivid base colors for main communities/practices. Use tints for variants. Ensure distinguishability (check with a color-blind simulator).
    Color Blending: Blend overlapping community colors using CIE-LCh for perceptual uniformity. Label blends explicitly in legends or on hover (“CI + Circling”).
    Typography: Clear, legible fonts. Hierarchy via size and weight. Emphasize keywords (community names, dates).
    Icons & Glyphs: Use consistent icon set for event types or venue types (dance, music, outdoors). Ensure icons have text alternatives. Venue icons should contrast background fields.
    Animation: Use easing and duration (~300ms for transitions) for showing/hiding elements. For time scrubbing, animate the morph to help tracking. Avoid looping or continuous animations except maybe a gentle map background pulse. Always allow the user to pause or disable animations (for accessibility).
    Ambient Gradients: Community fields can be drawn with radial gradients or soft edges. Avoid sharp clipping that suggest boundaries.
    Feedback on Actions: Buttons and map markers should visibly respond on hover/tap. When an event is saved, briefly show a toast or icon check.

7. Prototyping & Implementation

    Front-end Stack: Use Leaflet (or Mapbox GL) for base map. Render custom overlays with SVG for accessibility. A React (or Vue) architecture can manage states.
    Data Model:
        Event: {id, title, startTime, duration, venueId, communities[], tags[], price, hostId, accessibility, repetitionPattern}.
        Venue: {id, name, lat, lon, type, accessibilityInfo}.
        Community: {id, name, color, description, tags, entryGuidelines}.
        Person: {id, name, photo, followedCommunities[], attendingEventIds[], suggestedCommunities[]}.
        FieldState (for rhythm): {areaId, timeBucket, intensity, communityWeights, events[], regularityScore}.
    Field-State Generation (Sample Algorithm): Aggregate events by discrete time bins (e.g. “Thursday PM”, “Saturday AM”). For each bin and location cluster, compute:

    ini

    intensity = f(totalEvents, avgAttendance)
    communityWeights = normalize(sum weights of events by community)
    regularity = measure of how often similar events appear weekly (e.g. countRecurring / totalWeeks)

    Adjacency Scoring (heuristic): As sketched earlier, weight by:

    markdown

    score = 0.4 * ParticipantOverlap 
          + 0.3 * CommunityOverlap 
          + 0.2 * PracticeTagSimilarity 
          + 0.1 * VenueProximity

    where e.g. ParticipantOverlap = (# common attendees) / (avg attendance).
    Rendering Engine: Create a “Field Engine” module that takes data and stance mode, and outputs render instructions (SVG paths, circles, lines). This abstracts logic from React Leaflet code.
    Performance: Batch-render static overlays; throttle map update on drag. Use Canvas for heavy cases if needed (see [25] for trade-offs). Pre-calculate as much as possible (e.g. rhythm fields once per day).
    Prototyping Tools: Figma or Sketch for UI mockups; d3.js or plain SVG for interactive prototypes. Test small vs large data sets. Use browser dev tools to simulate color vision deficiency.

8. Microcopy and Tone

    Inviting, Non-Prescriptive: Use friendly, gentle language. E.g. “Discover what’s alive nearby” (not “Attend events now”).
    Empowering: E.g. “You’re all caught up” instead of “No events.” “Suggest to community” rather than “Flag event”.
    Transparency: For recommended items, use explainers: “Because you follow CI Aarhus” or “Popular with your circle.”
    Humble: Avoid absolute claims. “May interest you” vs “You must join”.
    Inclusive: Avoid jargon; use plain language. Provide optional tooltips for specialized terms (“CI” → “Contact Improvisation”).
    Community Feel: Use “we/our community” subtly to build solidarity, but mainly “you/your” to center the user.
    Contextual tips: e.g. “Need help? Check out community guidelines.”

9. Validation Methods and Metrics

    Usability Testing: Regular sessions with target users (facilitators and participants) to test flows: stance selection, event discovery, community onboarding. Observe confusion or delight.
    Diary Studies: Have a small group use the app for a few weeks and log how it affected their participation.
    Pilot Launch Metrics: Track KPIs such as weekly active users (WAU), event RSVP conversion, community growth rate, net promoter score (NPS).
    A/B Tests: Experiment with home-page variants (e.g. one big window vs two, CTA wording). Measure clickthrough into sections.
    Accessibility Audit: Run tools (axe, Lighthouse) to catch violations; test with screen readers (NVDA, VoiceOver). Ensure map labels are read.
    Community Health: Qualitative feedback on whether communities feel supported (through surveys or interviews with stewards).

Appendix: Key Patterns & Checklist

    Home/Orientation Page:
        Single main question or CTA; 3–4 preview windows maximum.
        Use person’s name and location contextually (e.g. “Back in Aarhus”).
        Use visual previews (small map, icons, list items) not just text.
    Map Visuals:
        Different modes have distinct legends and styles.
        Always show why something is highlighted (“3 people from your CI group attending”).
        Zoom triggers level-of-detail change (cluster vs unfold).
    Events & Communities Pages:
        Community page includes values, onboarding tips, and “how to enter”.
        Event page shows host, price, accessibility, who’s going (with circles or names).
    Facilitator Tools:
        After creating event, immediately invite to “Explore interested communities”.
        Allow editing and duplicating events.
    Performance & Accessibility:
        Check mobile responsiveness (menu collapse, readable text).
        Keyboard shortcuts (e.g. arrow keys for timeline).
    Design Justice:
        Represent diverse practitioners visually (avatars can show gender/race diversity).
        Tune algorithms to avoid reinforcing only majority preferences.

In summary: apply classic UX wisdom (structure, hierarchy, feedback) to a novel “field-based” paradigm. Make the invisible rhythms visible, but always give user clarity and choice. The design should embody openness and guidance, not dictation.

